description.value: 10 beads made of different shapes and materials. A: Bead in the shape of a Lupin bean, somewhat square with rounded edges, quite thick, both halves are divided by a sharp well defined edge. The material seems to be obsidian or black stone, incredible well polished and shiny. B: Three spherical beads, one of the broken into three fragments, made of some glass material in a green colour. The material did not seem to have been fired high enough as the core shows separate lumps that didn't melt properly. The broken one is covered in salt accretions. C: Elongated spherical bead made of faience with a white glazing, broken at one end. Greenish inclusion in the core. D: One barrel shaped bead made of bone. E: One spacer-bead, preserved in two segments, made of faience with remains of a yellow glaze. F: One disc-shaped bead with a high width, made of light green faience. G: One flattened spherical bead made of white faience. H: One disc-shaped bead made of ostrich eggshell.

description.value: several beads made of stone and faience A: barrel-shaped bead made of a black and white colour, one copper alloy fragment stuck to its surface, like a wire with a circular section, corroded and broken off. It has a length of 0.80 and thickness of 0.2 cm. A second patch at the surface shows remains of a second copper alloy fragment. B: small stone pebble with another copper alloy fragment stuck onto the surface, same thickness 0.2 cm as in A and length is 0.70 cm, as seen on the sketch originally joined to A C: six and a half small barrel-shaped beads made of faience, few remains of a whitish glaze, no colour preserved, most beads have no glazed preserved at all. One of the beads has few remains of copper alloy stuck onto the surface as well. This suggests that the whole assemblage was part of bracelet or something similar. D: disc-shaped bead made of ostrich eggshell

description.value: Capped beads with a reef-knot clasp: a string of thirty-nine bright-blue glazed composition spherical beads capped with silver and a gold knot-clasp. Some of the beads still have a glassy surface. The caps of silver consist of discs varying slightly in diameter, with a hole in the centre over which a tube is soldered. The tubes cover an inner cylinder made of a rolled length of copper pushed into the opening in the bead. One bead has a disc missing and only the tube remains. The gold reef-knot clasp is made in two halves, each stamped out. On the underside of one half is a flat plate cut by a central groove. On the flat underside of the other half, mounted on a strip of gold, is a flange which fits into the groove and joins the two halves together.

description.value: A string composed of forty long convex bicone beads of amethyst with gold foil caps and an uninscribed amethyst scarab. The beads are graded in size, the largest at the centre. The gold foil caps are made from pieces of sheet gold folded in at the boring at each end of the beads. On the beads whose caps are missing glue can be seen which once held the foil in position. The back of the scarab bears incised lines indicating the head and wing-case divisions; the legs are shown by rough scoring.
